answer:
A local static variable is common to all instances of the function. And it has static duration. Which means that it is not created each time the function is called. Hence a static variable retains its value across function calls.

int sum(int n)
{
    static int a = 0;
    a+=10;
    return n+a;
}
int main()
{
    int x=sum(10);//x is 20
    x = sum(12);//x is 32 as a in function is now 20
    x = sum(4);//x is 34
}

A global static variable is of course have static duration like any other global variable. But it has internal linkage. Which means that this variable is visible only inside the file where it is defined.

A static function has internal linkage too. So unlike other function which by default are extern, a static function is visible inside the file(compilation unit) where it is defined.

file1.c
#include<stdio.h>
static void hello()
{
    printf("Hello world\n");
}

file2.c
int main()
{
    hello();//produces linker error as hello function is not available here
}

Auto variable is a block variable, it has no linkage and it is created and destroyed each time the block runs.  By default all local variables are auto. Hence you rarely see auto keyword being used.An auto variable is visible only in the block where it is defined.

register keyword tells the compiler to store the local variable in CPU register for faster execution of code. It has block scope.

One restriction with register variable is you can not use & (address of) operator with these.

Global variables can not be  auto.

Keyword "volatile" tells the compiler that the value of the variable may change any time due to external events and compiler should not optimize this variable.
e.g.
volatile int m;
-----
-----
m=0;
while(!m)
;
Though the loop looks redundant as it does nothing, compiler will not remove the loop as m may change due to some hardware events.

