answer:
Scope of a variable is visibility of variable. And lifetime is how long is the variable alive, and when it will be destroyed.

auto - automatic variables have block scope and their lifetime is as long as the block is running. By default local variables are automatic. You can specify auto keyword - which is not needed. So if the block gets called multiple times, these variables are created and destroyed each time.

A variable declared outside of any functions is a global variable. Its scope is entire program and lifetime is from begining of program to end of program.

static variables are created at the begining of the program and are present till the end of the program. The scope depends on where these are defined. Local static variables are visible inside the block and global static variables are visible in the translation unit. Static variable have a default value of 0.

external variables are global variables with external linkage. They are visible in the entire program.
e.g.

file1.c
int gl1;/*global variable*/
static int gl2;/*static gloabal.Not accessible in other files*/
int print_num(int n)
{
     int a1;/*auto variable. Only visible in this function*/
    static int a2;/*retains its value across function calls*/
     a1 = n;
     printf("%d",a1);
}
int main()
{
     int b;/*auto variable*/
     b = a1;/* error. a1 has block scope*/
     b = a2 ;/*error. a2 has block scope*/
     b = gl1+gl2;/*no error gl1 and gl2 are 0*/
     print_num(b);
     print_num2(b);
}
file2.c
extern int gl1;/* no error*/
exern int gl2;/*linker error. gl2 has file scope*/
void print_num2(int a)
{
    a +=gl1;/*no error*/
   printf("%d",a);
}

